{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8cf7bb36-960b-40a4-8052-3a7195d36e82","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance **per HTTP request** — each request is a natural scope boundary. In MAUI, there's no equivalent boundary. The app has essentially one long-lived scope, so `AddScoped` behaves like `AddSingleton`. Your DbContext is never recreated between navigations, meaning the change tracker accumulates stale entities.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient<MyDbContext>()`** — new instance each time it's injected.\n2. **Use a DbContext factory:**\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n   Then inject `IDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>` and create short-lived contexts:\n   ```csharp\n   using var db = _factory.CreateDbContext();\n   ```\n\nThe factory approach is generally preferred — it gives you explicit control over the context lifetime.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fb1388fa-09da-4302-a6b9-8131b8251cd6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common issue when migrating from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping, specifically with `AddScoped` and DbContext lifetime behavior.\n\nThis is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request (each request is a \"scope\"). In MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request — the app has a single long-lived scope (essentially the app's lifetime), so `AddScoped` behaves like `AddSingleton`. This means the DbContext is never disposed/recreated between page navigations, causing stale data, change tracker accumulation, etc.","outputTokens":398,"requestId":"5021:224BB2:1CD5205:1FF7759:69FA9273"},"id":"9c59a602-4fbd-4f87-9da8-5eab518b9d2b","timestamp":"2026-05-06T00:59:41.879Z","parentId":"3deb6875-256a-4479-962b-c2864dd8db65"}
